@node editorsdesk "From The Editor's Desk"
@toc contents
		     @{fg shine}-= From The Editor's Desk =-
		          @{fg text} by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}

Hello and welcome to another issue of WhatIFF? - the magazine for the 
creative Amiga user!  It is unbelievable that as I write this we are at
the end of March, time is flying by.  This issue will be the last in the
monthly format, from here on the magazine will come out every other month.
Originally the idea was to do a monthly format magazine like Amiga World 
or Amiga Report but the Amiga scene is much smaller and not as active as
during time of those magazines.  If we expanded our magazine to cover 
games we could do a monthly magazine but there the market is saturated 
with other better magazines covering games and more.  As such it is 
increasingly difficult to fill the magazine with content on a monthly 
basis, especially since most of the new releases are games.  By moving 
into a bi-monthly format it will provide more time for the contributors to 
create their content and as a result the magazine will grow in size
 ... hopefully.

As I write this the cherry blossoms are blooming in Japan, it is a truly 
beautiful time of year, the weather is finally warming up and it is
nice to be able to have the windows open all day long.  I find that I am
energised when the sun is out, and it has made writing this issue of the
magazine a bit easier.  We have some nice articles for you this month, a
review of AmiKit for the Raspberry Pi 400, USB mouse dongle battle and
AmiGemini, something I am particularly excited about.  The guides section
has an article from @{"John Scolieri" link johnscolieri} about unbricking
your Indivision AGA MK2cr, which I can attest to is not a nice experience.
In addition we have the OctaMED, Lightwave and Brilliance 101 series 
continuing plus a short tutorial on creating your own Gemini capsule.

There have been some exciting news regarding new Amiga hardware, the 
Maggie chip and new SAM systems are of particular interest.  The latest
issue of Amiga Addict has a review of the A500 Mini and I am looking
forward to receiving my copy and reading about it.  Finally we welcome
back @{"Kevin Saunders" link kevinsaunders} aka Invent, with his articles
on game graphic design and last but not least an interview with PiMiga
creator Chris Edwards.  All in all I think this issue has turned out
nicely and should (hopefully) be an entertaining read.  As always if you
have any comments or want to contribute to the magazine please send an
e-mail to: submissions@whatiff.info

Thank you for taking the time to download and read this magazine, I hope
that you enjoy it and find the content useful.  Until next time!
  
@endnode


@node news "All the latest news about our favourite computer!"
@toc contents
 	   @{fg shine}-= News and Aminet Uploads for March 2022 =-@{fg text}     

 - = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = -

	     	  @{"  AMINET UPLOADS FOR MARCH 2022  " link aminet} 

March is a lovely time of year, we have the cherry blossoms coming into
bloom in Japan and the weather is relatively warm.  Regarding the Amiga
it has been an exciting month with two new hardware announcements.
 
@{b}Amiga Future Issue 155 Released - 5th March 2022@{ub}
The longest standing print Amiga magazine keeps going with issue 155
available.  Issue 155 covers, Review Putter, Special Custom Chip 
Replacements, Workshop UTF-8 on the Amiga and so much more.

@{b}DiscreetFX Monthly Giveaway - 12th March 2022@{ub}
Every month DiscreetFX will be giving away 2 copies of Vultures to
Vampires Vol.1 and Vol.2.  To be in with a chance to win a copy send an
e-mail to: discreetfx@gmail.com along with your current Amiga and/or
Vampire configuration.  Please write "I want to take a bite out of 2022
and am willing to win Vultures to Vampires Vol.1 or Vol.2 to read in
Dracula's study!" - Good luck to everyone! 

@{b}Sam460LE Production Started - 19th March 2022@{ub}
We do live in lucky times with another new Amiga going into production.
To put in your pre-order just visit: shop.acube-systems.biz and look
for Sam460LE, the board is currently selling for 292.80 euros.

@{b}AmiKit XE/Pi 11.6.1 Update - 20th March 2022@{ub}
The latest update for AmiKit XE now allows you to run Amiga OS3.2 though
you will need an earlier OS release for installation such as AmigaForever.
After the installation you can install Amiga OS3.2.

@{b}Amiga Addict Issue 11 On Sale! - 21th March 2022@{ub}
If you do not know abot Amiga Addict yet then you are missing out on one 
of the best English language print Amiga magazines out.  Taking cues from
Amiga Action and Amiga Format, it is a colourful and entertaining read of
the Amiga with reviews of games of old and new.  The current issues covers
reviews of the A500 Mini, h0ffman's Knightmare, interview with Nick Veitch
the former editor of Amiga Format.

@{b}New 3D Chip Maggie From Apollo - 28th March 2022@{ub}
Apollo have shown a sort preview of a new 3D chip they are working on
named the Maggie.  It looks like it will be an additional chip to the
Apollo SAGA chipset.  You can see a short demo of the chip in action
on YouTube, search for Apollo Maggie Chip.

@{b}Sound Module For ZZ900 Available - 29th March 2022@{ub}
The multi functional graphic card ZZ900 has a new sound module ZZ9000AX
that is being sent out in the first batch to buyers.  If you purchase
one now, it will be sent to you in the second batch from June 2022.

Well that is it for Amiga news for March 2022, it has been a relatively
quiet month but some great updates and lots of new reading with Amiga
Future and Amiga Addict out.  If you have anything that you would like 
to be featured in the What IFF? news section contact us at: 
submissions@whatiff.info
  
@endnode

