@node amikitpireview "AmiKit For Pi400"
@toc reviews
	   	@{b}@{fg fill}*AmiKit Pi400 Review - March 2022*@{ub}@{fg text}

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Product Name@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}  Reviewed by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
AmiKitPi

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Hardware/Software Requirements@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
Raspberry Pi 400/Pi4
Amiga Kickstart
Workbench 3.1.4 or higher disks
Windows/Mac OS to transfer the image file to a MicroSD card

@{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Machine Used For Testing@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}
Raspberry Pi400

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}AmiKit Comes To The Pi@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu} 
The Raspberry Pi the little computer that can has played a large role in
in the Amiga scene of recent.  From HDMI adapters to the accelerators like
the PiStorm, the Pi computers have given new life to the aging Amiga 
hardware.  With the advent of the Pi400 we now have two complete Amiga
desktop solutions available.  In the last issue of WhatIFF? we looked at 
the PiMiga created by Chris Edwards.  For this issue we will have a look 
at it's competitor the AmiKit for Pi.  This review we will look at 
installation, how well it runs, usability and if it is a worthy purchase 
over the free PiMiga.

Since it is not possible to download a demo of the package, you will need 
to pay upfront and there are three options.  The first option gives you 
the standalone package with no software updates, the second one comes with 
one years worth of updates and support, finally the third option has three
years of updates and support.  The prices are in euros and start from 
19.95, 29.95 and 49.95.  Payment options are via PayPal, Debit/Credit Card
or CryptoCurrency, I chose the first option and paid via PayPal.  Quickly
I received an e-mail with a download link to the AmiKitPi image.  It comes
in at a rather slender 8.8gb.  Installation was easy with the Raspberry Pi
Imager writing the file quickly to my SD card.

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Installation On The Pi400@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}  
It is from here that the installation becomes a bit more involved.  First 
you will need to prepare a 3.1 Kickstart rom and CD/Disk image(s) of 
Workbench 3.1.4 or higher.  Luckily I had a copy of Amiga OS 4.1 from the 
time I had entertained purchasing a SAM board.  Everything needs to be 
copied onto a USB stick that can be plugged into the back of the  Pi400.

To get everything started, insert the micro SD card and turn on the Pi400,
it will take a short while to boot but shortly you will be presented with 
a Linux desktop and several icons.  When the desktop has appeared it is 
time to plug in the USB stick.  Before opening the USB stick you will need
to resize your SD card if it is over 16gb in size.  This can be done by
opening the folder named 'START HERE Required Files', then opening 
'GParted', you will be asked enter the password which is: amikit.  Another
window will open where you can resize the partition to take advantage of 
the full capacity of your card.  For more details on this have a look at
the installation instructions available from the AmiKit website or on 
YouTube.  Once you have completed resizing the SD card, you need to setup 
Wifi which is done easily via the task bar.  Now it is time to copy the 
files you prepared beforehand.  When a USB stick is plugged in a USB icon 
will appear on the desktop, copy the kickstart and iso/adfs to the folder 
called 'START HERE Required Files', if you have a copy of the AmigaForever 
DVD then all you will need to do is copy the image over.  When everything
has been copied over, you can finally start AmiKit by clicking on 
'AmiKit'.

An Amiberry application window will appear and it is from here that you 
can setup access to the DVD/CD iso from the 'Hard drives/CD' option on the 
left side of the window.  Once you have found your iso image, you can 
click on Start to get the installation underway.  It will ask you if you 
want to install or download certain updates, obviously you should say yes. 
A short while later it will finish and ask you to restart AmiKit.  Double 
click on the AmiKit icon, then 'Start' from Amiberry and the remaining 
installation will start, it is here that you can choose the resolution and 
colour depth.  Once it has finished its thing, you will be able to enter 
the AmiKit Workbench screen.

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}First Impressions@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}   
You are welcomed with a very sleek and modern desktop that looks similar 
to AmigaOS 4.1.  There are a few disk icons at the top of the screen and 
several larger ones at the bottom, along with displays of time and free 
memory at the bottom right of the screen.  Overall first impressions are 
very good, it undeniably looks clean and professional.  The icons are 
colourful and sharp, the menu bar has a nice gradient along with the 
window frames.  It looks like it has been tailored for 1080p resolution.  

PiMiga uses ScalosWB, AmiKit has optedfor DOPUS, which does not look that 
different until you open a window and see the various disk options not 
usually available in standard Workbench window.

Most of the software can be accessed from the start menu located at the 
bottom of the screen.  You are provided with a limited selection of games
and software such as MicrogoldEd. Perfect Paint, YAM, SimpleMail, AWeb,
DizzyTorent, ChaosPro and music players: Hippo Player, DeliPlayer and Eagle
Player.  I was surprised to see there were no word processors, other art
packages like DeluxePaint or 3D rendering software since these programs
would take advantage of the higher spec hardware.  It is also possible to 
run Linux software from within the Amiga environment, and this can be done
from the same start menu.  You have access to LibreOffice and Chromium, it
is also possible to run other Linux software via the RabbitHole feauture.

Overall I found the experience quite pleasant, it is obvious a lot of work
has gone into making everything look very nice and organised.  It is 
relatively easy to find what you want and most software seems to run 
without issues.  This is probably due to a smaller selection of software
allowing the creators to spend more time on making sure things work.

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Not Quite Perfect@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
The whole AmiKit experience is very sleek and it works very nicely on the
Pi400 however there are few niggles.  Firstly I found the menu bar to be
difficult to read, when right mouse clicking you are able to see the other
options.  Within AmiKit the menu items are in white text and the menu bar
background is a blurred grey colour.  This makes it a bit difficult to see
the text, this is exacerbated by the small font used.  My monitor is 21.5"
and having text that small makes me need to lean in to the monitor.  If 
you are using a smaller monitor you might also have trouble, or this 
could just be my eyesight getting worse as I age.  Another issue I had was
with EaglePlayer, my chosen audio player.  The AmiKit devloper used a skin 
that makes using EaglePlayer extremely difficult.  The main programme uses
a huge graphic made to look like a cassette player but the buttons are 
tiny, it was difficult to figure out which one I had to push to play and 
stop a song and don't get me started on how I managed to quit the program.  

In general I usually I don't have issues with software GUI on the Amiga 
but this time it was very frustrating.  To add insult to injury there was 
a paltry choice of modules available, if I am going to pay 20 euros I 
would expect a little more content.  Finally I need to mention the mouse
pointer.  Running Workbench/DOPUS in 1080p creates a very small mouse
pointer that it becomes difficult to find it.  The developer might want to
take a page out of PiMiga and use a custom mouse pointer made for higher
resolutions.

Aside from those bumps in the road AmiKit is a very nice piece of work, it
creates a very modern and clean Amiga environment.  The ability to use 
Linux from the Workbench provides an additional level of usability.  
AmiKit has a problem though and that is PiMiga.  As nice as AmiKit is, it 
is still 20 euros more than PiMiga's 0 euros.  They both essentially do 
the same thing but while PiMiga maybe not be as polished as AmiKit it has 
much more content installed.  This in a way negates the RabbitHole feature 
since PiMiga has more software already installed allowing you to do more 
than with AmiKit.  I really liked AmiKit and will probably still use it 
though the GUI issues and lack of content mean that I will not use it as
much as I had hoped.

@{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Final Thoughts@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}
AmiKit Pi version is a very stylish and polished Amiga dekstop environment
providing a modern and powerful Amiga experience.  It looks fantastic and
a lot of work must have gone into making the experience as nice as it is.
The RabbitHole feature is surprisingly useful, being able to run a modern
web browser within the Amiga environment is pretty cool.  However it does
suffer from some ghosting effect on windows.  Apparently this can be 
reduced by enabling 'display compositing' from the Linux side.  

I really want to like AmiKit, it looks amazing and is a lot of fund to use
but the issues with the menu bar, lack of software and mouse pointer make 
it a little hard to swallow the 20 euros.  If it was the only Amiga 
desktop for the Pi400 perhaps it would seem a better deal but with PiMiga 
out there it feels a bit over priced for what it does.  PiMiga is easier 
to install, has more content, does not suffer from GUI issues and is 
available for free.   AmiKit is a bit more complicated to install, has 
less installled software and while it looks a lot nicer it also suffers 
from some serious crippling GUI issues.  

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Pros and Cons@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
+ Relatively easy to install
+ Looks fantasic
+ RabbitHole feature is very good
- Can seem expensive when compared to similar software
- Has some GUI issues

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Scores@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
Ease of use: 80%
Documentation: 90%
Value for money: 75%
Overall: 81% - WhatIFF? Silver            
@endnode

@node amigeminireview "AmiGemini Review"
@toc reviews
 	    	  @{b}@{fg fill}*AmiGemini Review*@{ub}@{fg text}

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Product Name@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}  Reviewed by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
AmiGemini 0.7 (18/02/2022)

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Available From@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
Aminet - www.aminet.net/comm/net/AmiGemini - Free
Author: Karl Jeacle 

@{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Hardware Requirements@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}
Kickstart/Workbench 3.0+
68020+
TCP/IP stack, AmiSSL

@{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Machine Used For Testing@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}
Commodore Amiga 1200
Classic WB + 3.2 Kickstart 
  
@{b}@{u}@{fg shine}What Is Gemini@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}
Let's be honest, surfing the modern web on classic Amigas is not exactly
a nice experience.  Modern web pages are full of cpu hungry javascript,
large 24bit images and lots of CSS.  Our humble computer of which is
over 30 years old just can't cope with these websites.  What if there was
a version of the Internet that was not image heavy and more like the old
ANSI text of the BBSes of yore?  Well in 2019 a new Internet protol was
launched, Gemini Protocol, the tag line is: 'Gemini is heavier than
gopher but lighter than the web'.  Each page or site is called a Capsule
and can only be accessed by a Gemini browser.  Some websites provide 
automatic conversion so the Capsules can be viewed on a traditional 
browser.

Boiled down it is a text only version of websites with a very, very simple 
markup language.  The protocol is still relatively new and has not gained 
commercial recognition yet but hopefully over time more websites will 
feature Gemini Capsule content.  The beauty of this standard is that it 
runs very nicely on an Amiga, since there are no heavy images to process.
In February a new version of AmiGemini was released on Aminet and I have
been using it for the last month.  Before being able to launch AmiGemini
you need two pieces of software installed: AmiSSL and a TCP/IP stack, both
can be found for free or demo versions of the Roadshow TCP/IP stack will
work as well.  Once you have these installed you can run AmiGemini from
anywhere but I would recommend installing it properly to your hard disk.

Upon loading the software you are presented with a simple screen, the 
majority of which is taken up by the black window and some simple ANSI 
text logo and links to other Gemini Capsules.  It is clean and easy to 
understand which is just how software should be.  At first glances it 
looks like a standard web browser with the usual Back, Forward, Reload,
Home and Stop buttons.  You are unable to access http websites so you
will need to know the Gemini Capsule address already or use the links
provided on the start screen.  Clicking on Amiga Links brings you to a
short list of Amiga centric Capsules and you may even spot WhatIFF?'s
Capsule among them.  Included in the list are: Amiga Future News, Aminet
Latest, Amiga Ireland, UHC Tools, GemLogs Amiga Tales and Karl's Amiga 
Page.  Below those are some other links to news websites such as The
Guardian and Huffington Post to ABC.

@{b}@{u}@{fg shine}AmiGemini In Use@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}    
AmiGemi has been a real pleasure, having the simplicity of text only 
content makes it easier to read and also the Amiga does not struggle with
downloading complex scripts or image data.  It brings me back to the days
of being on a BBS but with the whole world now available to me.  AmiGemini
may only be in version 0.7 but it is already a very stable programme.  It 
is very fast, except when clicking on a link but I think this is probably
due to my installation of AmiSSL.  My TF1260 does not have an FPU, the 060
build of AmiSSL seems to look for an 060 with an FPU.  To make AmiSSL work 
on my system I had to choose the 020 version of AmiSSL.  As such the speed 
of decoding the Gemini protocol is not as fast as it could be.  Aside from 
that I have found myself spending more time online via my Amiga in within 
the Gemini space.  While I do not deny we cannot live with out the way the 
web is now, there is a lot of un-neccessary junk making the browsing 
experience a waste of time.  Gemini brings introduces a stripped and clean 
version of the Internet for those who just want to get to the information 
they need.  The nice thing about the Gemini protocol is that it can also 
link to outside websites.  As an example our WhatIFF? capsule links to the 
www website so users can download the magazine directly to their Amiga 
via AmiGemini with the minimum of hassle.  To learn more about how to 
create a Gemini Capsule please visit to this quick @{"Gemini Tutorial" link geminitutorial} 
we have in this issue.

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Final Thoughts@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
The Gemini protocol will not be for everyone, it can not and will not 
replace the web as we know it now.  However it is a great way for 
accessing information quickly and without hassle.  I think this would be
a fantastic protocol for libraries to employ.  A simple interface for
accessing content around the world without the distractions of image heavy
websites and perhaps even more security.  For myself I great enjoy reading
the news from AmiGemini, searching for other Capsules about the Amiga or
anything that interests me.  I spend less time waiting for images and 
scripts to run and more time enjoying the content.  Even with a modern 
computer and browser AmiGemini is a faster way for accessing information.
I am greatly looking forward to the next version and see what improvements
Karl will implement.  Co-incidentally we have an interview with Karl 
Jeacle in an up coming issue. 

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Pros and Cons@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
+ Simple and easy to use
+ Stable and fast
+ Renders Gemini Capules very nicely
+ Able to handle outside links on other Capsules
- Needs AmiSSL which does not support TF12060 fully

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Scores@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
Ease of use: 85%
Documentation: 95%
Value for money: 100%
Overall: 83% - WhatIFF? Gold
@endnode

@node usbbattlereview "USB Battle Review"
@toc reviews
			@{b}@{fg fill}*USB Battle Review*@{ub}@{fg text}

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Product Name@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}  Reviewed by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
USB Mouse Adapter:jamy_retro
USB Mouse Adapter JERRY: electronika4you

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Available From@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
eBay - jammy_retro & electronika4you

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Special Hardware and Software Requirements@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
Any Amiga though A600 and A2000 will require extension cables

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Machine Used For Testing@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
Commodore Amiga 1200
KS/Workbench 3.2
Indivision MK3, TF1260

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}USB For Your Amiga@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
As the Amiga hardware ages it is becoming harder to find original hardware
especially peripherals such as the Amiga mouse.  What used to cost on 
average £15 now can go for as much as £75.  This is obviously silly money
so for many of us USB mice are the only realistic route to using a mouse
with our aging hardware.  Luckily due to the simple nature of USB adapters
and there being no lack of parts buying a USB mouse adapter is not going 
to burn a hole in your wallet.  For this review we will take a look at two 
USB adapters readily available on eBay.

Both adapters require mice that use the PS/2 protocol, it should be 
possible to use the scroll wheel with both adapters as long as you are
using Workbench 3.2 or have scroll wheel support installed in 3.1.

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}USB Adapter From jamy_retro@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
The first adapter we will look at is the smallest and cheapest of the
two.  It has no brand name and is just listed as 'Amiga USB mouse Adapter
for A500, A1200 (right fix), A2000, A4000', the current listing price is
$9.99 + Shiping (To Japan it was $7.50).  This is a pretty good price and
one of the cheapest ones I could find.  The adapter itself is quite small
with a grey plastic case and black USB port sticking out.  Total length
is 4cm from the mouse port to the USB port.  There are no LED lights or
any other writing on the adapter.  Plugging it in is very easy, it is not 
too tight or lose, though I recommend using the screws on the side since
it is very sensitive to any movement.  When I did not have it screwed in 
and moved the Amiga it lost the connection requiring me to turn off the 
computer and re-insert the adapter.

In use I had no problems with it recognising my mice, there were no issues
with lag or smoothness.  It fit the A1200 with out any problems and
I think the A500 will be fine but the A600 you will most likely need an
adapter if you wish to have a mouse and joystick plugged in.  The small
footprint is an added bonus since it gives you more space at the back of
your computer.  According to the listing it does not mention Atari 
compatibility so if you are planning to use this on another system be 
aware it might not be compatible.

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}JERRY USB Adapter From electronika4you@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}  
The second adapter we are looking at is the JERRY, this is almost double
the length of the first adapter coming in at about 6cm, it encased in 
metal with the JERRY logo and a single red LED near the USB port.  It can 
be found on eBay by searching for 'JERRY USB adapter', the listing cost is 
$44.80 + Shipping (To Japan it was $1.99).  The JERRY differs from the 
first adapter in that it can also be used with Atari computers, which 
would explain the much higher asking price.  Like the other adapter 
though you will need an adapter to use it with an A600 and Atari ST.  

Due to the length it needs more space at the back of the Amiga and is made 
even longer when a USB mouse is plugged in.  When I first plugged in the 
adapter it did not recognise my mouse, I had to press the left mouse 
button a few times before the red LED blinked and recognised my mouse.
Once the mouse was set up I did not have any other issues, movement was
smooth and there were no issues with the mouse buttons.  
 
The JERRY also supports scroll mice with the appropriate version of 
Workbench or drivers installed.  Aside from the initial setup I did not 
encounter any issues, it also susceptible to losing connection if the 
adapter is not screwed in tightly.  Unfortunately my JERRY broke quite 
quickly, I think this might be due to the length, as it is easy for cables 
to get caught on it.

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Which USB Adapter Should You Go For?@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
If you are not concerned about using the adapter with an Atari ST then the
first adapter is hands down the best choice.  It was the easiest to 
install, had less issues and is the smallest.  Finally it is 1/4 the price
of the JERRY.  The JERRY seems to be more advanced but at the end of the
day I just want an adapter that allows me to use a USB mouse with the least
hassle and this adapter does that at a great price.


@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Pros and Cons@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
Adapter One			   Adapter Two 
+ Small footprint		   + Supports Amiga and Atari ST
+ Cheapest of the two              + Has more features
+ Just works                       - Too long, sticks out of the Amiga
                                   - Expensive

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Scores@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
Adapter One			   Adapter Two 
Ease Of Use: 100%                  Ease Of Use: 90%
Build Quality: 90%                 Build Quality: 85%
Value For money: 100%              Value For money: 85%
Overall: 96% - WhatIFF? Gold       Overall: 86% - WhatIFF? Silver

@endnode

@node tf1260betafirmware
@toc reviews
			@{b}@{fg fill}*TF1260 Alpha Firmare Install and Review*@{ub}@{fg text}

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Product Name@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}  Reviewed by: @{"John Scolieri" link johnscolieri}
TF1260 Alpha Firmware

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Available From@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
www.exxoshost.co.uk.

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Upgrading the Alpha firmware update on the TF1260!@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}

In Issue 2 we went over how to setup and install the Beta firmware update 
on our TF1260 and now we're updating to the latest Alpha firware so
let's go:

1. Follow the exact same hardware setup as in Issue 2.

2. Download the Alpha firmware files from Stephen at www.exxoshost.co.uk.

3. Follow the same steps to set up the software files as seen in 
   Acill's YouTube video at https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sleia9n8fIg 
   using the updated Alpha firware files. IMP- make sure to copy over
   the '.bat' files from Beta files over to the Alpha folder as well.

4. Connect your C232HM-DDHSL-0 USB to MPSE cable to your TF1260 and 
   PC via USB cable and open up your Shell and type 'flash.bat' 
   to start the firmware update and within 20 or so seconds the
   process is completed.	

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}How Fast Can We Go?@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
Now that the Alpha firware update is completed it's time to compare
Beta vs Alpha results.  All tests carried out running AmigaOS 3.2.1
with SysSpeed v2.6.

Quick summary: The biggest difference was in chip ram read/write speeds
as there was a 66.7 increase. There was also a nice increase from  
2.7MB/s to 3.9MB/s on the onbaord IDE with the new ehide.device update.

Note: On my Rev1 68060 I unfortunately I couldn't over clock it to 
62.5Mhz with the Alpha firmware or even 58 or 55Mhz but in testing some 
intense 060 specific demos I honestly saw no difference in performance? 
Perhaps this is becuase of the big jump in chip ram speed or other 
internal changes?

Stability wise the Alpha firmware update is solid on my system.

@{fg shine}@{u}@{b}Conclusion@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
Definitely worth the while to update despite the lack of 
overclocking compared to the Beta firware.  Looking forward to the next 
update!

cheers,
@endnode

