@node lightwave101 "Lightwave 101 -  Smoothing Your Object"
@toc guides
                          @{b}@{fg fill}*Lightwave 101 - Part 3*@{ub}@{fg text}
                           Written by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
@{b}@{u}@{fg shine}A Whole Boing Ball@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}
In the last issue we had mirrored, welded and coloured your Boing Ball but
you may noticed when rendering that it looks rather angular.  The smooth
lines you would associate with a ball are not there.  For this part of the
Lightwave 101 tutorial series we will smooth out the surface to create a
more natural looking Boing Ball.  So let's get on with it and load your 
object from last time.  Once you have done that, you might want to zoom in 
a little so you will be able to see what will happen to the ball.

The first step we will take is to sub-divide our polygons into smaller 
elements.  In most guides that I have read trippling your polygons is the
one of the best ways to start a good render.  It is very easy to do this 
in Lightwave.  Click on 'Polygon' then choose 'Triple' under the Transform
heading.  You should now see that your polygons have become triangles, now
you may also notice that the this has not smoothed out the surface yet.  
We will need to apply another tool but it is good that we have converted
the polygons to triangles first.

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Subdivide Smooth@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
Next we will be using the Subdivide tool and this requires triangles hence
the reason for trippling our polygons.  If you try to use Subdivide with
quad polygons you will get an error asking you to triple the polygons 
first.  Right onto Subdividing, you will find the Subdivide button in the
'Polygons' and under the Transform heading.  Click on 'Subdivide' and a
new requestor will pop up.  Click on 'Smooth' and leave the Max Smoothing
Angle as is, then click on 'OK'.  Depending on how powerful your Amiga is
it will take a little time to calculate but shortly you will see your ball
transformed into a smoother object.  

Save your object and let's render it out!

@{b}@{fg shine}@{u}Time To Render@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}  
Hopefully you have saved your object and are now in the Layout programme.
Load your object via 'Objects' button, you have to be careful here when
moving your object and camera.  It can be easy to forget which one you 
are editing, so always double check what you have chosen in the View and
Edit sections.  First of all let's move the camera, under View and Edit
make sure Camera is selected for both.  Holding down the left mouse button
will adjust the Z axis i.e. how close you are to the object and the X axis
from left to right.  Holding down the right mouse button will allow you to 
adjust the Y axis i.e. up or down.  Position the camera anyway you like, 
once you are happy it is time to adjust the lights.  Once again double 
checking have a look at View and Edit and click on 'Light' for both.  Most
likely you will see the inside of your Boing Ball and so we want to pull 
it out to shine on the ball.  Using the left and right mouse buttons pull
the light out.  It helps to rotate the light around to find where the 
camera is located so you can orientate yourself and don't have a light 
shinning incorrectly.  

At this point I should mention that it is important
to have set your Key Frame.  If this is not done, when you render your 
scene all the camera and light positions will not be used.  To create a 
Key Frame we look at the bottom of the screen.  You will see Selected Item
 Current Frame, Key Frame and the button 'Create Key'.  These will be 
useful later on when animating but for the moment we are only interested 
in 'Create Key'.  Click on 'Create Key', in the panel that pops up leave
the Frame at 0 since we are not animating, then click on 'All Items' since
we want to save the positions of all the objects, lights and camera then
click 'OK'.  Be aware your camera and light settings might not have been 
saved, if so you will need to adjust the light and camera again then click 
once more on 'Create Key' leaving everything as is (it should have saved 
the selections you made last time) and then 'OK'.  At this point you might 
want to save your scene.  This is as simple as going to 'Scene' and click
on 'Save Scene'.  Soon we can render your object, but before doing that 
let's add a bit of shininess to your surface.  Currently your object is
not using any texture maps so we can adjust the surface directly, go to
'Surfaces' and find Specular Level near the middle of the panel.  Clicking
on the two arrowed button you can adjust the Specular level of the object
and surfaces.  

Next look at Reflectivity, again have a play with the slider and to see 
what kind of effect it will have when rendering.  It is a good idea save 
your test renders so you can see how to improve them.  To save an image 
you need to go to 'Record' and then click on 'Save RGB Images', you can 
choose whether you want to save an 8-Bit HAM or 24 Bit RGB image.  Once 
you choose them you will be asked for save location and name.  So that 
is it for this time, good luck with rendering your image and playing 
around with the lights and camera.  

See you next time for the fourth installment of the Lightwave 101 series.  
@endnode  

@node brilliance101 "Brilliance 101 - Reflection and Gradient"
@toc guides
		  @{b}@{fg fill}*Brilliance 101 - Part 3 Reflection and Gradient*@{ub}@{fg text}
                           Written by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
@{u}@{b}@{fg shine}True Brilliance@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
Up to now we have been working in the standard version of Brilliance, the 
one that has a maximum of 256 colours available.  For this part of the
tutorial we are goiing to visit TrueBrilliance.  It is from within True
Brilliance that the real power and versatility of Brilliance is realised
using the HAM8 mode to great effect.  We will be using the gradient and
transparent tools for the next parts of our image.  You may be thinking
why do we need to do this in True Brilliance, the reason being that True
Brilliance works on the images in a 24Bit buffer, so when working with
gradients and transparency having a 24Bit buffer makes a big difference
in your image quality.  Let's get started shall we?

@{u}@{b}@{fg shine}Gradient Fill@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu} 
This is one of my favourite tools in TrueBrilliance, you can create some
truly emotive imagery when using the tool.  If you have not done so yet,
load up your image with the perspective floor.  You should have a black
sky at the moment, let's add some colour to sky.   Left mouse click on
the 'Gradient' tool, then 'Clear' on the left of the screen.  You can
see a black rectangle box in the middle of panel, scroll over to as far
left as it will go and choose a colour.  For example I chose 0 68 255.
Next scroll all the way over to the right, again as far as it will go.
Choose another colour, I chose 255 0 51, since I want to have the classic
pink to dark blue sky gradient.  Once you have chosen your two colours
you can check it by left mouse clicking on the  'Dither' slider button
but do not move it.  A horizontal preview of the gradient will be shown
above the panel, if you feel there is too much banding you can reduce by
increasing 'Spread' on the right of the panel.  Experiment by increasing
the number and then check with the 'Dither' button.  

Once you are happy with the colour choice it is time to fill the screen.  
First off we should close the 'Gradient' panel since we will not need it 
at the moment, this can be done by left mouse clicking on it.  We will 
need a two tools for a gradient fill, first the 'Fill' tool, left mouse 
click on it.  Next we will go to the  'Draw Mode' tool, right mouse click 
on it to bring up the panel.  At the far right you can see - Horizontal, 
Verticle, Linear, Highlight, Spherical and Radial.  We will investigate 
these more in a later tutorial but for the moment we want Vertical since 
we are creating a gradient sky.  Once you have chosen 'Verticle' press the 
space bar to hide the panel and click in the black part of the image and 
wait while a beautiful gradient will scroll down the screen.  Now that we 
have that let's add a bit more pizzazz to the image.  Double left mouse 
click on the 'Rectangle' tool so it becomes a 'Filled Rectangle' tool.  
Next right mouse click on the 'Transparent' tool, move the slider to 25% 
opacity.

Here comes the fun part, make sure you have the 'Filled Rectangle',
'Draw Mode' and 'Transparent' chosen, then draw out a rectangle covering
the entire floor, making sure to not touch the gradient sky.  Quickly 
you will see a reflection of the gradient on the floor, pretty neat right?

The added colour afforded by HAM8 and the ability for TrueBrilliance to
work in a 24Bit buffer allow you to replicate these modern techniques. Who
needs Photoshop when you have TrueBrilliance?  Now that we have the 
gradient sky and a reflection of it on the floor we will create some 
objects to put on the floor and reflect them, however that is for next 
time.  As always have a play around with Brilliance, it is an incredibly
powerful piece of software that still has relevance today.

See you next issue and keep creating!

@{u}@{b}@{fg shine}Additional Thoughts @{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
When we had created the marble floor, we had used the standard Brilliance
however if you want to create something with a bit more colour you can 
use TrueBrilliance to draw a marble floor or even import a marble texture.  
Creating a larger version of the floor texture will also make it look less 
jagged when using the perspective tool.
  
@endnode           		   

@node indivisionagamk2cr "Fixing Your Bricked Indivision AGA MK2cr"
@toc guides
    	        @{b}@{fg fill}*Fixing Your Bricked Indivision AGA MK2cr*@{ub}@{fg text}
                       Written by: @{"John Scolieri" link johnscolieri}

@{u}@{b}@{fg shine}How to unbrick your IndivisionAGA Mk2 flicker fixer/scan doubler@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
You messed around with some settings in the Indivision AGA config tool as 
you've done many times and you're sure you didn't hit the 'Apply' or 
'Save' buttons but yet again you boot up to a black screen.

No problem you say, let me just boot from my boot/rescue disk and then 
just go and re-apply my settings in the Indivision AGA config tool BUT
alas you still boot into a black screen !?  This is because the config 
cores on the the MK2cr are corrupted and now your Amiga can only boot up 
to good old 15Khz aka old RGB Amiga monitors or if you're lucky you've got 
a modern monitor that can sync down to 15 Khz.

This happened to me recently and I was fortunate enough to have my Amiga 
1080 monitor handy to get my trusty Amiga 1200 Tower booting up with my 
boot disk so all is solved now right?......well not yet because when you 
go into the config tool in sys:Prefs nothing happens? I tried some assigns 
to point the config tool to the Devs:Indivision folder where the cores are 
present but still nothing.

@{u}@{b}@{fg shine}Outside Help@{ub}@{fg text}@{uu}
At this point I reached out to Jens from Individual Computers 
(manufacturer of the IndivisionAGA among other fine Amiga hardware as I'm 
sure many, if not all, amiga users already know) for help fearing that my 
board was bricked forever :-( After going back and forth in the Individual 
Computers support forum with no luck and losing hope fast Jens suprised me 
with this revelation "This is my so-far-unreleased attempt for an MK2 
recovery disk.  It will flash the default config and then re-start the 
flickerfixer.  However, it will *not* double-check if the flicker fixer 
comes up properly, so you may only get a picture back after a power 
cycle."

WoW! Okay hmm I thought 'unreleased' eh BUT there's some hope so I 
downloaded the ADF file from here, don't forget to add - https://

forum.icomp.de/core/index.php?attachment/2935-agamk2-recovery-adf-zip/

and ... BANG! I am happy to report it worked !!!

Ah the joy when your Amiga is back up and running again lol.  Big time 
thanks and kudos to Jens!  I would have been more than happy to help test 
the MK2 recovery disk but alas the first test was a charm and I'm sure 
this will be a massive help to other IndivisionAGA Mk2 users world wide!

Cheers.
