@node octamedsequencing "How to Sequence and Structure Songs in OctaMED"
@toc guides
            @{b}@{fg fill}*OctaMED 101 - Sequencing Your Songs*@{ub}@{fg text}
                      Written by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
@{u}@{fg shine}@{b}Introducing The Block@{uu}@{fg text}@{ub}
Welcome back to another OctaMED tutorial, in the last three issues we 
examined the most commonly used commands in OctaMED.  Now that you can
build a simple track it is time to learn how to sequence your song.  This
can be one of the most confusing parts for first time users or those who
are used to different software.  I confess that I still do not understand
how to sequence a track in ProTracker, as such I am looking forward to
the ProTracker guide that will be coming after this series from 
MissMadLemon.

Well that is enough faffing around, let's get to the meat of this 
tutorial, the block.  A block in OctaMED is like a sheet of music, you 
can play the same block over and over or create new blocks and sequence
them into a song.  OctaMED blocks start by default at 64 lines but can 
go up to 1264 (This is in OctaMED Pro v4.0), most people stick to to 64 
lines, however drum and bass tracks have a tendency to use 128 lines.  
The block number can be seen in the left hand side of the screen above 
the edit window.

It can be most easily identified as under the button that says, NEW HERE
and has the numbers 000/000, the box on the left of the block is the
sequence number and by default it has the numbers 001/001.  Near the top
left you will see another window that has arrows on the right of it 
pointing up and down, this is where you can sequence your track. At the
moment the box just shows 00.  The 00 indicated the block number, if you
have a look at the block counter under NEW HERE you will see it only shows
000/000.  Too add a new block have to go the BLOCK button, then click on
NEW BLOCK.  When you do this you will see the block counter change to 
000/001. The left 000 indicates which block you are on, the right numbers
indicate the total number or the last block number.  You move easily 
through the blocks by holding the right Shift key and using the UP/DOWN
keys.  If you use the LEFT/RIGHT keys with the right Shift key held down
you can then cycle through your instruments.

Lets create a simple beat on block 000 or 000/000, find a kick drum and 
lay it down every four lines.  Now let's go to our next block, so hold 
right Shift and DOWN, you will see your edits disapear and the 
block number changes to 001 or 001/001.  Repeat the same drum seqeuence 
and then load a snare drum and lay it down every other kick drum.  When 
you finished, click on PLAY BLOCK, while it is playing you can move 
between blocks using the Shift and UP/DOWN keys.  However if we click on 
PLAY SONG, it will only play the block 000 looped.  What we want to
do nex is sequence the track.

@{u}@{fg shine}@{b}Sequencing@{uu}@{fg text}@{ub}
It is quite easy to sequence a track in OctaMED once you understand how
blocks work.  Our first block is 000 and we want it to repeat twice.
First you need to make sure you are on block 000, using the 
Shift + UP/DOWN key combination, make sure you block number looks like 
this 000/001.  Next find the INS button on the left, click it three times
so that the sequence counter looks like this 0001/0004.  Using the down
arrow button click until the sequence counter says 0003/0004 click on the
plus button, click again on the down arrow and click on the plus button.
There you have it, you have now made a simple sequence for the begining
of your track.  Click on PLAY SONG and you can see in the left window
which block is being played.  If you followed the instructions correctly
block 000 will play twice and block 001 will play twice.  As you can see
it is quite easy to sequence a song in OctaMED, this power allows you to 
go back to a block or to create variations in your tracks.  

Have fun and next time we will look at how to copy and paste tracks and 
blocks helping you save time.    

@endnode               

@node geminitutorial "Create Your Own Gemini Capsule"
@toc guides
            @{b}@{fg fill}*Create Your Own Gemini Capsule*@{ub}@{fg text}
                      Written by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
@{u}@{fg shine}@{b}Building Your Own Capsule@{uu}@{fg text}@{ub}
In this issue we review AmiGemini, the Gemini browser that allows Amiga
users to view Gemini Capsules, in other words a Gemini page.  From a 
personal standpoint I believe the Gemini protocol is one of the best 
things to have happened to the Amiga of recent.  As you probably already
know, browsing the web on a standard Amiga without a graphics card is 
quite a painful experience at the best of times.  The Amiga is just not
cut out for the high resolution and colour websites that are common place
today.  Gemini allows computers to communicate over the Internet but in a
much lighter and less graphic intensive form.  If you have read my review
already you will know that I am very excited about this the new protocol.

What makes Gemini even better is that it is incredibly easy to make a page
or capsule and so for this tutorial we will cover the basics and where you
can host your files.

@{u}@{fg shine}@{b}The Basics@{uu}@{fg text}@{ub}
The markup language for Gemini Capsules is called Gemtext and is very easy
to learn.  You can use any text editor for creating your Gemtext, let's 
have a look at some of the basics.

	- Long lines get wrapped by the client software to fit the screen.
	- Short lines do not get joined together.
	- Write paragraphs as single long lines.
	- Blank lines are rendered verbatim i.e. if there is a line with no
	  text it will show as a blank line on the client.

	- There are three levels of heading:

	  #   Heading
 	  ##  Sub-heading
 	  ### Sub-subheading

	- You get one kind of list and can not nest them:

	  * Mercury
	  * Gemini
	  * Apollo

        - Lines that start with ''' will cause clients to toggle between 
	  ordinary and preformatted mode.

	- If you want to add a link, the text looks like this:

	  => https://example.com     This is an example of a http link.
	  => gopher://example.com    An example of a gopher link.
          => gemini://example.com    A Gemini link example.
     	  => sftp://example.com

The links will always start with => the text after the link is optional 
and if you do include it will hide the url link, showing only the text.
So as you can see it is very easy to create a page for Gemini, but if you
are still not sure, let's try and make a simple page.


	# Welcome to my Gemini Capsule

	This is a short text explaining about my capsule.

        ## Some of my favourite links.
        
	=>gemini://whatiff.flounder  Gemini capsule link to our site.
        =>http://whatiff.info/Issues/WhatIff1.01.lha   Http outside link.

There you are, that is a simple Gemini capsule that has two headings and 
two links, one for a Gemini page and one to a HTTP link.  When you save
the text file just remember to add the .gmi prefix on the end, so your
first page would be named: index.gmi  
As you can see it is very simple.  Hosting a Gemini Capsule is a little 
more complicated though and requires you to create a Github account and 
upload your Gemtext files there.  Then you need to link to the Gemini
hosting company you chose.  However I found [ http://flounder.online ] 
much easier to use and am currently hosting the WhatIFF? Gemini Capsule
with them.

If you end up making a Gemini Capsule, let us know and we will publish it
in the magazine.  Good luck and enjoy exploring the world of Gemini 
Capsules. 

@endnode               

@node amigaspeak "Welcome to voices of the people behind Amiga hardware and software."
@toc contents
           	@{fg shine}-= Amiga People - Chris Edwards =-@{fg text}

 - = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = -
 
For issue 4 we are very lucky to have an interview with the talented and 
charasmatic Chris Edwards the creator of the awesome PiMiga package.

 - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
@{b}Hello Chris, thank you for agreeing to this interview, to start with can 
you give a short introduction about yourself, i.e. where you're from, 
what you do etc.?@{ub}

Hello, my Name is Chris and I am an Amiga haulic.   

I am currently a Network Engineer.  I am also a former Commodore Cats 
employee.  "Cats" was a acronym for Commodore Amiga Technical support. 
Equivalent to a modern desktop support engineer. I live in Southern 
Pennsylvania , USA about 1 hr from former C= West Chester HQ.   I fix, 
review, repair Amiga and Amiga related products. I also am the current 
custodian of a project called PiMiga. A Amiga like tribute to what could 
have been. A modern take on the classic Amiga OS. Using multiple 
collections all piled into one pot of soup that works pretty good!

@{b}1. Chris you are known as an Amiga YouTuber and the creator of the PiMiga 
software installs, can you tell us a little about how you got into the 
Amiga?@{ub}

Long story on that one, but the abridged version is as follows: My family 
owned Carry-out restaurants through the 90's.  I was a starving teenager. 
I would eat for free there all the time. I also helped out now and then 
working on site in one way or another.  It was Autumn, maybe around 
November 1985?. 

A delivery driver came back and said that he just saw a customer that had 
the new Amiga everyone had heard about on TV, newspaper, magazines etc. I 
replied to him and stated they are not even available to the public yet, 
not until feb 86 or so, he assured me it was real. 

I called the customer back up and asked if I could come check it out 
(keep in mine i am like 18 or so yrs old drive a 1967 Ford mustang, have 
80's skater dude hair, acid washed jeans, etc.  Customer said sure! Come 
on over!  I bring over a peace offering of Steak and cheese subs and a 
few pops/soda/soft-drinks.  Turns out this person worked for Commodore in 
some fashion, and had the units before the main stores were to sell it, 
he said he was a commodore rep or something? He told me "this is number 45
of 50!" I was not paying too much attention to who he was, but I got to 
use the A1000 before the public really did.  Fun, colorful, (at the time 
compared to our slow other systems) it totally blew me away.  I had to 
have one. I must have stayed at this customers house for 4-5 hours, I had 
more food and beverages brought out to the place via our drivers at least 
one more time . (I remember eating food from our store twice) 

Several months later in 86 I purchased my own A1000 (my first Credit card 
charge in my life) , then a A500 for Christmas 87.  That started the lust 
which remains to this day. I currently own 21 Real Amigas, and numerous 
alternatives such as, PPC amigas, MorphOS, MiniMig's , misters, Pi's etc. 

@{b}2. Do you work on other systems other than the Amiga, if so, what are 
your favourite systems?@{ub}

Sure!  I love early Mac and Steve Jobs Apple, Tandy's, PC's , video games 
of all types,  I am a true nerd, but Commodore and its Amiga products are 
my favorites. 

@{b}3. What is the Amiga scene like in the States, is there a large retro 
scene similar to Europe and the UK?@{ub}

Amiga has always been a niche market here.  Commodore USA marketing was 
that of a joke in retrospect. 

I am part of a vast community of retro enthusiasts.  Not only for 
Commodore, but many other things.  Retro is alive everywhere on all types 
of systems and consoles. 


@{b}4. When did you start making YouTube videos, was it something you saw 
yourself doing everyday or as a hobby and why?@{ub}

2013, I made a video on how to fix your washing machine when it wont spin.  
I made it on a crappy Android phone (motorola Atrix) .  I did not re-start 
Amiga videos until 2016 or so, I did not think there was any interest in 
that old platform publicly. I always still used My Amiga 2000 by myself, 
and thought i was alone. I was wrong!  There is a thriving community and 
I am grateful to be a part of it. 

I continue to do Youtube Videos to help others with similar situations 
that I encounter in my Amiga life. or with other things.  I do community 
repairs for free minus shipping to help others keep their Amiga's alive. 
I now have to pre-screen them to make sure I am not just wasting my 
efforts for them to sell it on eBay! (which has happened). My Youtube 
channel has only a small part of the subs versus watchers. IF everyone 
who watched my videos just clicked subscribe it would help me out 
greatly. (It's like a 90 % unsubscribed watch my content)  I do this as 
a hobby, and a Job.  It's a massive effort to film, edit and post. 

@{b}5. Regarding PiMIga what first attracted you to the Raspberry Pi?@{ub}

The price versus power aspect. Such a small little device can do so many
things.  Was this my love for Amiga all over again?  Arm processors are 
gaining foothold in the mainstream world (new Apple chips ring a bell? ) 
soon I would love to see motherboards for sale with Arm chips, that could 
mean desktop systems, laptops or more!

@{b}6. When creating up the PiMIga installs, what did you find most 
difficult?@{ub}

More like combining. Getting everything to work as best as it can 
together.  Anyone who has used the Amiga for anything besides playing 
games knows this.  Programs do not always get along, you install one 
thing, this breaks 4 other things and by the time you stack hundreds of 
programs well it can be a tail chaser.  PiMiga is not just  a "creation"  
but more of a combination of many talented collections all bundled into 
the same book. I hope that by adding these collections into this story 
called PiMiga. It can share enjoyment and knowledge for a long time. 

@{b}7. How do you envisage people using PiMiga?@{ub}

I just enjoy seeing the community Re-discover their love of what was, 
what could have been, and what is more than just games.

@{b}8. What would you like to do in later versions of PiMiga?@{ub}

There are many things, ideas, thoughts, suggestions that are considered. 
It takes around 1 year to make a newer version. Many other great 
distributions have come out since. I look to many for inspiration and 
ideas.  Secrets, secrets..

@{b}9. Do you have plans to create versions of PiMiga for other hardware?@{ub}

No, The RPI seems to work the best for what i need it for. A small 
universal box of wonder that I can prevent it from booting PiMiga at all 
without a rom.  Providing a non working product until the user provides 
their legally owned/purchased ROM file is the key.  That does not mean 
there are other ways around this, but that can be said for many things. 

@{b}10. What are your opinions of the current Amiga scene, do you feel we 
are at better place than before?@{ub}

I used to think "This is so much better". Then that changed. My work has 
been stolen, resold, and my own YouTube chan/videos have been under 
attack from a web store who resells everyones work. This has caused a 
delay in development of the next version. Also (it) cost me financially 
with view revenue.  Now pending litigation on this individual from 
multiple countries, people and projects. 

@{b}11. As hardware ages do you think the future of the Amiga will be solely 
through emulation or a combination of both?@{ub}

I repair Amiga's as I used to, well way more than I used to. As the 
hardware continues to age and degrade one day it will all be replaced by 
other sources.  Just like the owners. 

I will be a custodian of all of my collection as long as I can.  Then I 
hope someone else can enjoy them as I do.

@{b}12. What is your favorite model of Amiga and why?@{ub}

The Amiga 3000,  I have always said this is the best engineered Amiga 
that ever has been made.  Sure there were newer AGA machines and the like 
but those should have never been at the time.  There were plans on the 
table to continue the line with the 2200, and the 3400, then the 3000+.  
The AGA chipset would have been in them, Hese recreated the AA3000 in 
2019 with original prototype plans, so you can get one today if you're 
rich!
 
@{b}13. What Amigas do you own and which one is your main driver?@{ub}

I own every Commodore Amiga product model with the exception of the twin 
towers.  They are just out of my reach in todays prices. However if I find 
one that I can afford I will do my best to own them. 

My main driver is my A3000 setup, but I do different tasks on the 
different models.  I use them all almost daily in one way or another. 

@{b}14. Finally do you have anything you would like to say to current or 
future PiMiga users?@{ub}

Thank you for using PiMiga, the ScalosWB replacement that makes the old 
bland Commodore Workbench that and so much more.  This is NOT what it 
looked like, this is the vision of the future.  An homage what could have 
been, or at least an alternative to what could have been, and please read 
the instructions... 8^)

@endnode
